<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-566-008  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 566 008.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 18 1990 v24 n25 p59(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cold war redux. (the US Department of Commerce moves to block adeal for a fiber-optic communications network in the Soviet Union)(Data Stream) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The decision of the US Dept of Commerce to block the sale of afiber optic cable across the Soviet Union is surprising in lightof the recent talk of economic cooperation.andP;  The contract wouldhave involved US West Communications and would have resulted inthe construction of a data communications network capable oftransmitting at 565M-bps.andP;  This figure, while less than half thatof a state-of-the-art system, is still in excess of the 140M-bpsceiling endorsed by the US State Dept.andP;  Although security concernsare not without foundation, it seems a poorly conceived strategyto sell powerful computers and then restrict their networkcommunications capability in this manner.andP;  After all, the point ofsuch trade is to help former adversaries develop a strong economythat will function as a platform for peaceful cooperation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   U.S. West Communications Group Inc. (marketing).andO;Topic:     Technology transferExport controlsFiber OpticsSoviet UnionUnited States. Department of CommerceData Transfer RateUnited States.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>